y Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental or habitational name composed of a variant of the (placename) element <i>ved</i> ‘wood, forest’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Wedon was born about 1524, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son and 4 daughters with Mrs Jone Wedon."},"et":{"about 1524–":"umbes 1524–Surnud","1524–Female":"1524–Surnud","1544–Female":"1544–Surnud","1549–Female":"1549–Surnud","1552–Female":"1552–Surnud","1554–Female":"1554–Surnud","1557–1559":"1557–1559","1524–Male":"1524–Surnud","1557":"1557","1524":"1524","about 1549":"umbes 1549","1544":"1544","1554":"1554","1552":"1552","about 1524":"umbes 1524","about 1557":"umbes 1557","about 1554":"umbes 1554","about 1544":"umbes 1544","about 1552":"umbes 1552","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Wantage, Berkshire, England":"Wantage, Berkshire, England","England?":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"f